{"parse":{"title":"Repeating circle","pageid":17887911,"revid":847565683,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:12in_Repeating_circle.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/96/12in_Repeating_circle.jpg/220px-12in_Repeating_circle.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"222\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/96/12in_Repeating_circle.jpg/330px-12in_Repeating_circle.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/96/12in_Repeating_circle.jpg/440px-12in_Repeating_circle.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"856\" data-file-height=\"864\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:12in_Repeating_circle.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>12-inch repeating circle.</div></div></div>\n<div class=\"thumb tright\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:222px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Repeating_circle-CnAM_1842-IMG_4998-gradient.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/dc/Repeating_circle-CnAM_1842-IMG_4998-gradient.jpg/220px-Repeating_circle-CnAM_1842-IMG_4998-gradient.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"220\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/dc/Repeating_circle-CnAM_1842-IMG_4998-gradient.jpg/330px-Repeating_circle-CnAM_1842-IMG_4998-gradient.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/dc/Repeating_circle-CnAM_1842-IMG_4998-gradient.jpg/440px-Repeating_circle-CnAM_1842-IMG_4998-gradient.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"5500\" data-file-height=\"5500\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Repeating_circle-CnAM_1842-IMG_4998-gradient.jpg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Borda reflecting circle, on display at <a href=\"/wiki/Conservatoire_national_des_arts_et_m%C3%A9tiers\" title=\"Conservatoire national des arts et m\u00e9tiers\">Conservatoire national des arts et m\u00e9tiers</a>.</div></div></div>\n<p>Developed from the <a href=\"/wiki/Reflecting_instrument#reflecting_circle\" title=\"Reflecting instrument\">reflecting circle</a>, the <b>repeating circle</b> is an instrument for <a href=\"/wiki/Geodetic_surveying\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Geodetic surveying\">geodetic surveying</a>, invented by <a href=\"/wiki/%C3%89tienne_Lenoir_(instrument_maker)\" title=\"\u00c9tienne Lenoir (instrument maker)\">Etienne Lenoir</a> in 1784,<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> while an assistant of <a href=\"/wiki/Jean-Charles_de_Borda\" title=\"Jean-Charles de Borda\">Jean-Charles de Borda</a>, who later improved the instrument. It was notable as being the equal of the <a href=\"/wiki/Ramsden_surveying_instruments#great_theodolite\" title=\"Ramsden surveying instruments\">great theodolite</a> created by the renowned instrument maker, <a href=\"/wiki/Jesse_Ramsden\" title=\"Jesse Ramsden\">Jesse Ramsden</a>. It was used to measure the <a href=\"/wiki/Meridian_arc\" title=\"Meridian arc\">meridian arc</a> from <a href=\"/wiki/Dunkirk\" title=\"Dunkirk\">Dunkirk</a> to <a href=\"/wiki/Barcelona\" title=\"Barcelona\">Barcelona</a> by <a href=\"/wiki/Jean_Baptiste_Joseph_Delambre\" title=\"Jean Baptiste Joseph Delambre\">Jean Baptiste Delambre</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Pierre_M%C3%A9chain\" title=\"Pierre M\u00e9chain\">Pierre M\u00e9chain</a>.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Construction_and_operation\">Construction and operation</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Repeating_circle&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Construction and operation\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The repeating circle is made of two <a href=\"/wiki/Telescope\" title=\"Telescope\">telescopes</a> mounted on a shared axis with scales to measure the angle between the two. The instrument combines multiple measurements to increase accuracy with the following procedure:\n</p>\n<div class=\"center\"><div class=\"thumb tnone\"><div class=\"thumbinner\" style=\"width:402px;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Borda-repeating-circle.svg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/09/Borda-repeating-circle.svg/400px-Borda-repeating-circle.svg.png\" width=\"400\" height=\"300\" class=\"thumbimage\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/09/Borda-repeating-circle.svg/600px-Borda-repeating-circle.svg.png 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/0/09/Borda-repeating-circle.svg/800px-Borda-repeating-circle.svg.png 2x\" data-file-width=\"454\" data-file-height=\"341\" /></a>  <div class=\"thumbcaption\"><div class=\"magnify\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Borda-repeating-circle.svg\" class=\"internal\" title=\"Enlarge\"></a></div>Mode of operation:<br />(1) The instrument is aligned so its plane includes the two points to be measured, and each telescope is aimed at a point;<br />(2) Keeping the angle between the telescopes locked, the left (black) telescope is rotated clockwise to aim at the right point;<br />(3) the right (gray) telescope's position is noted, and it is rotated back to the left point.</div></div></div></div>\n<p>At this stage, the angle on the instrument is double the angle of interest between the points. Repeating the procedure causes the instrument to show 4x the angle of interest, with further iterations increasing it to 6x, 8x, and so on. In this way, many measurements can be added together, allowing some of the random measurement errors to cancel out.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Repeating_circle&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/Reflecting_circles\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Reflecting circles\">Reflecting circles</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Meridional_definition\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Meridional definition\">Meridional definition</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"/wiki/Grade_(angle)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Grade (angle)\">Grade (angle)</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Repeating_circle&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Daumas, Maurice (1989). <i>Scientific Instruments of the Seventeenth and Eighteenth Centuries and Their Makers</i>. London: Portman Books. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0-7134-0727-3\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-0-7134-0727-3\">978-0-7134-0727-3</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Scientific+Instruments+of+the+Seventeenth+and+Eighteenth+Centuries+and+Their+Makers&amp;rft.place=London&amp;rft.pub=Portman+Books&amp;rft.date=1989&amp;rft.isbn=978-0-7134-0727-3&amp;rft.aulast=Daumas&amp;rft.aufirst=Maurice&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ARepeating+circle\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class